      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou hast seen it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Whatever the wicked may imagine to the contrary, arguing from his own limited experience (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Psalm 10:11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 10:11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Faith triumphs over appearances, for it rests on the unchanging character of God, Who never ceases to ‘behold,’ to observe all that goes on upon the earth. Cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 33:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 35:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 94:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "mischief and spite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The words may be understood thus, of the wrong done; or, as in R.V. marg., of the suffering endured, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "travail and grief",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The first word inclines rather to the objective, the second to the subjective sense. Perhaps we might render: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "mischief and vexation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to requite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "with thy hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] More exactly as R.V., to take it into thy hand. God’s observation cannot fail to lead to action. In His own time He will take the matter in hand. Cp. P.B.V., which however, in opposition to the Hebrew accents, connects the words with the following clause, ‘That thou mayest take the matter into thine hand: the poor &c.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the poor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The helpless (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Psalm 10:8; Psalm 10:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 10:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 10:10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "abandons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (such is the literal sense of the word) himself and his cause to God, Who will never abandon him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thou art",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rather as R.V., thou hast been. It is an appeal to experience. The ‘fatherless’ (or ‘orphan’) is mentioned as a typical example of the friendless and unprotected, who are under God’s special guardianship. Cp. the primitive law of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff., reechoed in the latest utterance of prophecy, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
