  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou hast seen it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The most emphatic contradiction that was possible to the wicked man's \"He will never see it\" (ver. 11). God sees, notes, bears in mind, and never forgets, every act of wrong-doing that men commit, and especially acts of oppression",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". For thou beholdest mischief and spite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, perhaps, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "mischief and grief",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the \"mischief\" of the oppressors, and the \"grief' of the oppressed. (so Hengstenberg, Cheyne, and the' Speaker's Commentary'). Others refer both words to the feelings of the oppressed, and translate, \"travail and grief.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To requite it with thy hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Again the Prayer-book Version is preferable, \"to take the matter into thy hand,\" both for reward and requital. The poor committeth himself unto thee. He has no other possible refuge - therefore no other reliance. Thou art the Helper of the fatherless. The word \"thou\" is emphatic - \"Thou, and no other (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אַתָּה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").\" Psalm 10:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Now comes the confirmation of his cry to God: It is with Him entirely different from what the ungodly imagine. They think that He will not punish; but He does see (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the psalmist knows and confesses it: ראתה (defective  equals  ראיתה ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 35:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Thou hast seen and dost see what is done to Thine own, what is done to the innocent. This he supports by a conclusion a genere ad speciem thus: the trouble which is prepared for others, and the sorrow (כּעס, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") which they cause them, does not escape the all-seeing eye of God, He notes it all, to give it into (lay it in) His hand. \"To give anything into any one's hand\" is equivalent to, into his power (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 20:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and frequently); but here God gives (lays) the things which are not to be administered, but requited, into His own hand. The expression is meant to be understood according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 56:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 49:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : He is observant of the afflictions of His saints, laying them up in His hand and preserving them there in order, in His own time, to restore them to His saints in joy, and to their enemies in punishment. Thus, therefore, the feeble and helpless (read חלכּה or חלכּה; according to the Masoretic text חלכה Thy host, not חלכה, which is contrary to the character of the form, as pausal form for חלכה) can leave to Him, viz., all his burden (יהבו, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 55:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), everything that vexes and disquiets him. Jahve has been and will be the Helper of the fatherless. יתום stands prominent by way of emphasis, like אותם ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Bakius rightly remarks in voce pupilli synecdoche est, complectens omnes illos, qui humanis praesidiis destituuntur. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]